sentences: Françoise Renilde Irma Vanhecke  (born on 19 November 1957 at Kortrijk, Belgium) is a Belgian soprano, an artist, a pianist, a music researcher, music lecturer and a vocal coach.
Françoise Vanhecke is a Doctor of Musical Arts and received her PhD degree from Ghent University in 2017.
She has received her diploma for teaching singing and piano in 1981 from the Ministry of Education, Brussels (Belgium).
In 2000 she has received a Master's degree in Music, specialising in voice from the Lemmens Institute, Graduate School of Arts and Sciences at The Catholic University of Leuven.
Françoise Vanhecke participated in the first Queen Elisabeth Music Competition for singing in 1988 and received wide appreciation from the press and from the community.

At the Royal Conservatory of Ghent (Belgium) she has received the 1st prize opera, and a special prize "Coens & Willemot"; in 1982, she has received the 1st prize in piano; in 1980 she has received the 1st prize in singing and in 1979 a special prize "Aerens & Torck" in 1976 she has received the 1st prize for solfège.

At the Royal Conservatory of Ghent (Belgium) she has received the 1st prize opera, and a special prize "Coens & Willemot"; in 1982, she has received the 1st prize in piano; in 1980 she has received the 1st prize in singing and in 1979 a special prize "Aerens & Torck" in 1976 she has received the 1st prize for solfège.

In 1987 she has also received the palmo d'oro at International Chamber Music Competition For Lieder in Finale Ligure in Italy and the Radio 3 award for contemporary Belgian Chamber Music at the Orfeus contest.
In 1995 she wrote 'Jong bloed' on a text by the poet Guido Gezelle, for a broadcast on Classical Radio (Klara) in the town of Kortrijk.
From 1985 to present she has been a Professor of singing and opera, vocal ensemble and choir at the Regional Conservatory of Kortrijk (Belgium).
From 2009 until 2010 she has been a Professor in singing at the Erasmus College of Brussels (Belgium) at the School for audiovisual and performing arts.
